                          <a name="toc_item_2" style="text-decoration:none;" ></a><a class="resource-link" href="http://newsletter.foxepractice.com/t/r/l/iyikdlt/l/f/" style="text-decoration:none;color:#000;" >Pasta Primavera Sauce</a>
                        </h2>
                        <div style="background-color:transparent;background-image:url(http://i5.createsend1.com/ti/r/35/920/947/085545/csimport/email-video-frame_4.png);background-repeat:no-repeat;background-position:top left;background-attachment:scroll;width:347px;height:206px;padding-top:13px;padding-bottom:0;padding-right:0;padding-left:13px;" >
                          <a href="http://newsletter.foxepractice.com/t/r/l/iyikdlt/l/z/" style="text-decoration:none;" ><img width="334" label="Recipe Image" src="http://i5.createsend1.com/ei/r/CD/2F5/CD3/csimport/pasta.151442.jpg" height="186" /></a>
                        </div>
                        <p style="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:10px;font-size:16px;" >
                          <p>
	A rich, creamy sauce perfect for noodles or spaghetti and lightly steamed fresh vegetables.</p>
<ol>
	<li>
		In a blender place tofu, salt, food yeast, garlic, shallot, lemon juice and onion powder to process until very smooth and creamy. Add milk to blender to mix well.</li>
	<li>
		Pour into saucepan and heat until hot and steamy. (Do not boil.)</li>
	<li>
		Stir in chopped parsley, saving some to use as garnish.</li>
	<li>
		Use sauce with cooked pasta. Sprinkle with pine nuts, if desired.</li>
</ol>
